treatment.paragraph:
Distinguished from very similar 

S. mau

sp. nov.
by shape of female epigynal scape (shorter; tip wide and rounded rather than pointed; 
Fig. 95
) and by details of procursus tip (slightly different shapes of sclerites; 
Figs 92, 93
). From other species by male cheliceral armature (shapes of frontal apophyses; 
Fig. 94
) and by widened and sclerotized tip of female epigynal scape.

Known from Mount Kenya only (
Fig. 27
).
